    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i have a huge dataset with like 500 features and i know most of them are probably just noise, which one would be better to use? and why does L1 actually force them to zero while L2 just makes them small? i don't really get the intuition behind the math part",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you have a huge dataset with many features, and you suspect that most of them are just noise, L1 regularization (Lasso) might be a better choice. L1 regularization can help you identify the most important features by forcing some of the coefficients to become exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. This can simplify your model and potentially improve its performance by focusing on the most relevant features.\n\nL2 regularization (Ridge) tends to distribute the coefficient values more evenly, reducing the impact of less important features but not necessarily zeroing them out. This can be useful when you want to keep all features in the model but still want to reduce their impact.\n\nThe reason L1 regularization can force coefficients to zero while L2 regularization just makes them small is related to the nature of the penalty terms. L1 regularization adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients, while L2 regularization adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of the coefficients.\n\nMathematically, the L1 penalty term is |w|, where w represents the coefficients. This means that if a coefficient is zero, the L1 penalty term will also be zero, and the model will not be penalized",
      "source": "target",
